01:14.720 --> 01:16.160
Yeah, I come from a pretty poor background.

01:17.040 --> 01:20.720
A little terrorist house next to the railway. Got one brother, one sister.

01:21.920 --> 01:25.840
I was always very good at maths growing up. So, I think if you grew up in East London,

01:25.840 --> 01:30.560
you know, when I was a kid, we could literally see that the skyscrapers in Canary Wharf going up

01:30.560 --> 01:34.480
when we were kids. You can't ever assume you're just going to go into banking, right?

01:35.120 --> 01:37.920
So, that was sort of the path I thought I'd go on.

01:38.880 --> 01:43.280
I got expelled from school when I was 16 for a, I normally call it a drug-related incident.

01:44.240 --> 01:45.840
What was it?

01:46.560 --> 01:48.320
It was a cannabis, you know.

01:48.320 --> 01:49.040
You were expelled?

01:49.600 --> 01:50.640
Yeah, yeah, 16.

01:50.640 --> 01:51.600
Just for smoking cannabis?

01:52.320 --> 01:55.760
I think I sold about Â£2 worth of cannabis, which I wouldn't call it a sale.

01:57.040 --> 02:00.720
Yeah, I was young and I don't condone such things, but it happened back then.

02:00.720 --> 02:03.920
So, I was sort of stuck at home, gave me a bit of a kick up the arse,

02:03.920 --> 02:07.680
and I was sort of studying for my exams, but I did well in my exams and, you know,

02:07.680 --> 02:09.440
managed to get good A-levels and went to go to LSE.

02:10.160 --> 02:12.480
So, LSE, I don't know if you know people from LSE.

02:12.480 --> 02:13.920
It's a bit of a London School of Economics.

02:13.920 --> 02:15.760
It's a bit of an investment bank in Bootcamp.

02:16.960 --> 02:19.840
And I kind of figured I'd just go there, kill the exams.

02:19.840 --> 02:22.880
I would study maths and economics and get a job as a trader.

02:24.880 --> 02:26.080
That is super hard.

02:26.080 --> 02:28.480
Well, exactly, to get the job.

02:28.480 --> 02:32.240
No, maths for a degree is, because I know people that did maths at LSE,

02:32.240 --> 02:35.200
and they were really good maths students at A-level or whatever,

02:35.200 --> 02:37.360
but university level maths is incredibly demanding.

02:37.360 --> 02:39.120
I mean, you must be really good at maths.

02:40.080 --> 02:41.520
It was my thing as a kid.

02:41.520 --> 02:41.840
Yeah.

02:41.840 --> 02:43.440
Yeah, I won a few competitions.

02:43.440 --> 02:44.640
Math was my thing as a kid.

02:45.200 --> 02:46.640
It's just sort of the way my mind works.

02:48.640 --> 02:51.360
But I thought I could just go and just kill the maths exams and get a job.

02:52.080 --> 02:55.760
But I remember sort of coming back second year, and suddenly,

02:55.760 --> 02:58.960
everyone at LSE is just, they start talking in acronyms,

02:58.960 --> 03:04.160
CDSEs, M&As, MBOs, you know, CDOs, IBD, and I was thinking,

03:04.160 --> 03:04.880
what is going on?

03:04.880 --> 03:06.240
I didn't know anything.

03:06.800 --> 03:07.920
I spoke to a friend and he was like,

03:08.320 --> 03:10.320
you have to apply for 35 internships.

03:10.320 --> 03:12.480
And you hope you get one, and then that's how you get a job.

03:12.480 --> 03:15.760
And all of these guys, LSE,

03:16.560 --> 03:20.160
LSE is literally full of kids of Russian oligarchs

03:20.160 --> 03:23.600
and the Chinese Politburo, this international billionaire

03:23.600 --> 03:24.320
sending the kids to LSE.

03:24.320 --> 03:26.000
And they'd all been prepping from when they were kids.

03:27.200 --> 03:31.520
They'd all started a charity and checked through the Sahara Desert.

03:31.520 --> 03:33.760
How long did it take you to work this out at the LSE?

03:33.760 --> 03:35.040
How long did it take you to work out,

03:35.040 --> 03:37.440
okay, the people I'm now studying with at university,

03:37.440 --> 03:39.920
it's not like the creme de la creme of the kids at school,

03:39.920 --> 03:42.320
which was what you think it is before you go to university,

03:42.320 --> 03:44.080
but it's actually people I've never met before.

03:44.080 --> 03:45.760
I remember I was in the math department,

03:45.760 --> 03:47.680
which is a bit of sort of, you know what math guys are like.

03:47.680 --> 03:50.560
And we went on like this sort of away day, like very early on.

03:50.560 --> 03:53.920
And I brought like a two liter bottle of like white lightning cider

03:54.800 --> 03:55.760
on the coach.

03:55.760 --> 03:57.360
And I was like, I put some cider, everyone was looking at me

03:57.360 --> 03:58.160
like I was insane.

03:58.160 --> 04:00.800
And I remember thinking, this is not like what I saw in the movies.

04:02.160 --> 04:04.480
But I was, to be honest, when I was a kid,

04:04.480 --> 04:06.480
I was like, man on the mission, I'm going to get this job.

04:06.480 --> 04:07.520
Nothing's going to stop me.

04:07.520 --> 04:10.720
And that's why it was quite dispiriting to realize that basically,

04:10.720 --> 04:12.640
you have to send all these CVs and cover letters,

04:12.640 --> 04:14.800
and everyone, you've got to fluff it with all this stuff, right?

04:14.800 --> 04:17.040
Like I played clarinet at the Royal Albert Hall,

04:17.040 --> 04:18.240
you know what I mean, this kind of stuff.

04:18.240 --> 04:20.640
And literally, I was fluffing pillows at DFS.

04:20.640 --> 04:22.960
That's all I had, you know, I tried to be a grime rapper,

04:22.960 --> 04:24.240
you know, you can't put that on your CV.

04:24.960 --> 04:27.920
You know, I had the little jacket with cadaverous crew in on the back of it.

04:27.920 --> 04:30.720
But like, so I was thinking, how am I going to get this job basically?

04:30.720 --> 04:32.240
And I didn't know what to do.

04:32.240 --> 04:34.800
So I just figured like, I didn't make a single application

04:35.440 --> 04:39.360
because I knew I would never beat these guys on CV and cover letter.

04:39.360 --> 04:42.960
Like there's nothing, literally, I'm fluffing pillows at DFS in Bekton.

04:42.960 --> 04:44.400
You know, I'm not going to get a job with that.

04:44.960 --> 04:47.680
So I figured I would just like try and kill these exams

04:47.680 --> 04:52.480
and like be very sort of like loud about it and hope somebody notices.

04:53.280 --> 04:57.280
And basically, somebody did notice because a guy from near above said,

04:57.280 --> 04:59.920
just I never even met the guy, came up to me in the library one day and he said,

05:00.560 --> 05:02.560
Citibank has one trailer you to a card game.

05:02.560 --> 05:03.840
It's a maths game.

05:03.840 --> 05:05.280
You win that game, you can get a job.

05:05.280 --> 05:09.120
And I was sort of my ears pricked up because it's like maths.

05:09.120 --> 05:10.000
I'm good at maths.

05:10.000 --> 05:10.720
I'm good at games.

05:11.360 --> 05:12.160
So let's just do this.

05:12.160 --> 05:12.320
Right.

05:12.320 --> 05:13.840
And he explained like the rules of the game to me.

05:14.480 --> 05:16.160
And then I went to the competition.

05:16.160 --> 05:17.040
I won the LSE round.

05:17.040 --> 05:18.560
And then I basically just stopped going lectures.

05:18.560 --> 05:20.960
And I just, all I did was study this one game,

05:20.960 --> 05:22.800
which was like a stupid little math game.

05:22.800 --> 05:23.680
What was the game?

05:23.680 --> 05:24.480
It's like a card game.

05:24.480 --> 05:25.680
It's like a poker style game.

05:25.680 --> 05:28.000
They make it basically like everyone has a card

05:28.000 --> 05:29.680
and there's another three cards in the middle.

05:29.680 --> 05:33.200
And you just essentially you make bets using a trading style mechanism

05:33.200 --> 05:34.880
of what the sum total of everyone's cards will be.

05:34.880 --> 05:36.240
So it's probabilities basically.

05:36.240 --> 05:38.880
Citibank, well, this is actually interesting.

05:38.880 --> 05:42.320
You say that because the way I won the game was,

05:42.320 --> 05:45.280
I knew that all the mathsy guys would just calculate

05:45.280 --> 05:48.240
the statistical expected value, which meant that

05:50.560 --> 05:52.720
if someone had a high card, they'd quote high prices.

05:52.720 --> 05:54.720
And if someone had a low card, they'd quote low prices.

05:54.720 --> 05:56.800
And you could just buy, sell, buy, sell, buy, sell.

05:56.800 --> 05:59.920
And it's kind of, it's amazing it was that easy.

05:59.920 --> 06:03.840
And other people probably should have realised what I was doing.

06:03.840 --> 06:06.240
But I think this is, I think, another thing

06:06.240 --> 06:08.000
which has sort of benefited me throughout my career.

06:08.640 --> 06:10.240
Because of the way that I look and the way that I sound,

06:10.240 --> 06:13.840
I think people just thought I was fucking an idiot basically doing mad stuff.

06:13.840 --> 06:16.000
Like, but it was easy.

06:16.000 --> 06:18.480
They were playing the numbers and I was playing the game basically.

06:18.480 --> 06:23.600
So I won that competition and the madness of it is what that meant was,

06:23.600 --> 06:25.840
you know, all these other guys who'd be like learning all these acronyms,

06:26.800 --> 06:29.040
you know, and sort of talking to like, you know,

06:29.120 --> 06:31.360
they were in the investment side, in the finance side,

06:31.360 --> 06:32.800
going to all these events.

06:32.800 --> 06:35.200
And here's me turning up on my internship.

06:35.200 --> 06:36.240
I didn't know anything.

06:36.240 --> 06:37.440
I didn't know a single acronym.

06:37.440 --> 06:38.560
I didn't know anything like that.

06:39.920 --> 06:42.640
And the madness thing of it all is, the traders fucking loved it.

06:42.640 --> 06:45.360
They loved me turning up like some kid from down the road.

06:45.360 --> 06:48.960
Like, just like, I don't know anything, but teach me and I'll do it.

06:48.960 --> 06:49.600
You know what I mean?

06:49.600 --> 06:54.400
And I think it kind of, you know, there's this myth of like the Cockney Wideboy Trader.

06:55.120 --> 06:55.840
But I don't exist.

06:55.840 --> 06:56.640
The Barrow Boy.

