because everybody needed dollars.

12:11.600 --> 12:13.680
And Citibank at this point is the biggest bank in the world.

12:13.680 --> 12:14.480
Yeah, at that point.

12:14.480 --> 12:15.120
Yeah, yeah.

12:15.120 --> 12:16.400
So they were lending a ton of dollars.

12:16.400 --> 12:17.280
And I remember sort of,

12:18.000 --> 12:18.800
I figured out what they were doing.

12:18.800 --> 12:20.160
I lent a ton of dollars too.

12:20.160 --> 12:21.920
And then I was, there was one guy who I worked with.

12:22.480 --> 12:23.760
He was like, he was a scouser.

12:23.760 --> 12:24.400
He was from Liverpool.

12:24.400 --> 12:25.840
He didn't go to university.

12:25.840 --> 12:27.840
And after I put my first big trade on,

12:27.840 --> 12:28.800
I went home and I thought,

12:28.800 --> 12:30.480
oh fuck, what if this trade goes wrong?

12:30.480 --> 12:32.560
So I went in the next morning, I spoke to this guy,

12:32.560 --> 12:33.360
this scous guy.

12:33.360 --> 12:36.160
And he said, I said, what's the risk on this trade?

12:36.160 --> 12:39.040
And he said to me, this trade will lose money.

12:39.840 --> 12:41.360
If the global banking system blows up,

12:42.160 --> 12:45.360
in which case you'll lose your job and I'll lose my job.

12:45.360 --> 12:46.640
And it'll be the end of fucking everything.

12:47.280 --> 12:48.080
But that's not going to happen.

12:48.080 --> 12:49.200
So we're going to make a ton of money.

12:49.200 --> 12:51.040
So you just cross your fingers and hope it works out.

12:53.200 --> 12:55.040
So the first couple of years, all I did was that basically,

12:55.040 --> 12:56.000
just lend these dollars.

12:57.440 --> 12:59.680
And that was super profitable in 2008, 2009.

13:00.320 --> 13:04.480
Then in 2010, that stopped being profitable.

13:04.480 --> 13:05.680
I remember this weird thing happened.

13:05.680 --> 13:07.440
The Swiss National Bank did something that fucked me.

13:07.440 --> 13:09.040
And I lost like eight million dollars in a week.

13:09.520 --> 13:11.120
And that's when I realized like,

13:11.120 --> 13:12.560
it's not really free money like that.

13:12.560 --> 13:14.960
And I have to start figuring out like a smarter way to make money.

13:14.960 --> 13:17.920
So your first year, 2008, you make 400,000 pounds.

13:18.640 --> 13:20.880
You clear for yourself personally, something like that now.

13:20.880 --> 13:22.560
Oh no, that was, that was 2008.

13:22.560 --> 13:24.720
So 2008, I started in June, 2008.

13:26.240 --> 13:30.960
2009, my boss who hired me quit basically,

13:30.960 --> 13:32.160
in the middle of the year.

13:32.160 --> 13:33.280
And how come?

13:34.800 --> 13:37.600
I think he made so much money in 2008 that like,

13:38.320 --> 13:39.280
he just thought, I'm going to quit.

13:39.280 --> 13:40.720
I'm going to like live the dream.

13:40.720 --> 13:42.960
I'm going to like build my house in California.

13:42.960 --> 13:45.520
And that's a whole nother story, which we can get into.

13:46.240 --> 13:51.120
But he quit and he said to me,

13:51.120 --> 13:52.160
you can ask me anything you want.

13:52.160 --> 13:54.480
And I said, what do I need to do to make 100 grand for the bank?

13:54.480 --> 13:57.200
At that age, so I would have been 20, just turned 22.

13:57.200 --> 14:00.160
100 grand in my mind was like the most money you could make.

14:00.160 --> 14:01.120
Like in a year basically.

14:01.120 --> 14:02.240
What do I have to do to make 100 grand bonus?

14:02.240 --> 14:03.120
You go, it's not possible.

14:03.760 --> 14:05.520
You need to make 10 million dollars for the bank.

14:05.520 --> 14:08.160
He said, I said, all right, I went back,

14:08.160 --> 14:10.720
put one massive bet on 12 million dollars by the end of the year.

14:10.720 --> 14:13.840
And then yeah, and I was expecting to get paid a bonus of like 100 grand.

14:13.840 --> 14:15.680
And I remember going to the meeting room and it was like,

14:15.680 --> 14:17.520
just under 400 grand on the piece of paper.

14:17.520 --> 14:18.880
And I remember looking at it and just being like,

14:20.240 --> 14:22.160
I remember, I could remember like it was yesterday.

14:22.160 --> 14:24.640
My boss was a massive guy and I pointed at the number.

14:24.640 --> 14:25.840
I thought it must be another number.

14:25.840 --> 14:27.280
I pointed at the number and I said, is it that?

14:27.280 --> 14:28.400
And he said, yeah.

14:28.400 --> 14:31.200
And I literally said, wow, that's a lot of money.

14:31.200 --> 14:32.000
How old are we?

14:32.000 --> 14:32.800
Just turned 23.

14:35.680 --> 14:38.880
And I think what is weird about that?

14:39.440 --> 14:40.880
You know, there'll be people who hear that story

14:40.880 --> 14:41.920
and they'll be like, that's fantastic.

14:41.920 --> 14:42.480
That's amazing.

14:42.480 --> 14:44.640
Like kids from poor background made a ton of money.

14:44.640 --> 14:45.360
That's really, really good.

14:45.920 --> 14:46.720
And it is good.

14:46.720 --> 14:48.720
And you know, I wouldn't be able to afford to do what I do now

14:48.720 --> 14:49.440
if it wasn't for that.

14:50.080 --> 14:54.320
But the actual experience of it was like weirdly quite traumatic.

14:54.320 --> 14:56.320
I remember seeing like, if I'd have had 100 grand,

14:56.320 --> 14:57.760
I would have gone home to my parents and be like,

14:57.760 --> 14:58.480
I got 100 grand.

14:58.480 --> 14:59.920
I would tell my mates, I got 100 grand.

15:01.280 --> 15:02.960
Yeah, I would have told my girlfriend about 100 grand.

15:02.960 --> 15:06.240
But like 400 grand just seemed like an inhuman amount of money.

15:06.240 --> 15:09.040
It felt like the kind of money that you couldn't tell anyone about.

15:09.040 --> 15:11.920
It felt like, I felt like, how can I tell my, I went out

15:12.960 --> 15:14.240
and I sat down next to this guy.

15:14.240 --> 15:16.320
I used to work this gas guy and he could see I was upset.

15:16.320 --> 15:17.680
And he said, go out and like sit down.

15:17.680 --> 15:21.360
And I remember just thinking like, I think about my dad.

15:21.360 --> 15:22.160
You know what I mean?

15:22.160 --> 15:24.240
My dad worked for post office for 35 years

15:24.240 --> 15:26.640
and he was probably never making much more than 20 grand.

15:26.640 --> 15:27.760
And he used to start work.

15:27.760 --> 15:29.440
He used to leave the house at like 5 a.m.

15:29.440 --> 15:31.680
And the train used to go past the back of my house.

15:31.680 --> 15:33.520
And my mum would wake me up and we try and look at him,

15:33.520 --> 15:35.120
like wave at him, go and pass the house.

15:35.120 --> 15:37.200
And obviously that's dark, you know, you see him

15:37.200 --> 15:40.560
and you think about how hard he worked day after day after day

15:40.560 --> 15:41.840
for 20 grand a year.

15:41.840 --> 15:44.640
And then here's me, just 10, 23, sitting at a desk,

15:44.640 --> 15:46.400
you know, for a year, 400 grand.

15:46.400 --> 15:47.760
It just seemed like-

15:47.760 --> 15:49.840
You were all of a sudden different to everybody you knew, right?

15:49.840 --> 15:50.960
You're sort of disconnected to them.

15:50.960 --> 15:51.440
Exactly.

15:51.920 --> 15:54.800
That is 100 grand is like a gift.

15:54.800 --> 15:56.720
400 grand like buys you out of your family,

15:56.720 --> 15:57.840
buys you out of your friend group.

15:57.840 --> 15:59.760
I remember like, I went around my mate's house

16:00.560 --> 16:02.480
and we were playing like Pro Evo.

16:02.480 --> 16:06.400
And they were all talking, a lot of them worked in finance.

16:06.400 --> 16:07.280
Oh, did you get a bonus?

16:07.280 --> 16:08.240
Oh yeah, I got five grand.

16:08.240 --> 16:10.000
Oh yeah, I got like seven grand.

16:10.000 --> 16:12.080
And then one of them said, did you get a bonus?

16:12.080 --> 16:13.120
And I didn't tell anyone.

16:13.120 --> 16:14.000
And I just thought, you know what?

16:14.000 --> 16:15.200
These are like my closest friends.

16:15.200 --> 16:16.480
I'm just going to fucking tell them, right?

16:16.480 --> 16:18.880
So I told them, oh yeah, I got 395 grand.

16:18.880 --> 16:22.400
And you could just like hear like the silence,

16:22.400 --> 16:25.440
like feel the room of this like shock.

16:26.240 --> 16:28.080
And it was almost, and then it started to feel like,

16:28.960 --> 16:30.880
it started to feel like a cruel thing to tell people

16:30.880 --> 16:31.840
in a weird way.

16:31.840 --> 16:33.200
I made this amount of money.

16:33.200 --> 16:35.600
And it was a, and it's, I know it's bizarre,

16:35.600 --> 16:37.200
but I think in a weird way it was a cruel thing

16:37.200 --> 16:38.000
to happen to me.

16:38.000 --> 16:40.080
And I know that sounds crazy, but it's just,

16:42.160 --> 16:44.000
that level of inequality, you know,

16:44.000 --> 16:45.760
I made a lot more than that in following years.

16:45.760 --> 16:46.320
You know what I mean?

16:46.320 --> 16:48.160
But like, it shouldn't exist.

16:48.160 --> 16:48.960
It shouldn't happen.

16:48.960 --> 16:49.760
You know what I mean?

16:49.760 --> 16:50.240
It shouldn't.

16:50.240 --> 16:52.880
And it's, don't get me wrong, right?

16:52.880 --> 16:54.960
I think that people who work hard and are talented

16:54.960 --> 16:56.560
and do good things should make money.

16:56.560 --> 16:58.160
I think we should live in a world where that is possible,

16:58.160 --> 16:59.280
100%.

16:59.280 --> 17:02.160
But like, people like me and people where I'm from,

17:02.160 --> 17:04.000
didn't even know that 400 grand was a thing

17:04.000 --> 17:04.960
somebody could make.

17:04.960 --> 17:06.080
I had no idea.

17:06.080 --> 17:07.760
And then like, I was thinking,

17:07.760 --> 17:09.440
if I've made 400 grand, what have the rest of these

17:09.440 --> 17:09.920
fuckers made?

17:09.920 --> 17:10.720
You know what I mean?

17:10.720 --> 17:11.760
I was just looking around,

17:11.760 --> 17:13.520
me thinking like, what is going on?

17:14.400 --> 17:16.640
So yeah, it was, it was a, it was a mad experience.

17:18.480 --> 17:20.880
You were city's most profitable trader globally

17:20.880 --> 17:22.240
at one point, is that correct?

17:22.240 --> 17:22.560
Yeah.

17:22.560 --> 17:23.920
So that was 2011.

17:23.920 --> 17:24.960
So basically like,

17:24.960 --> 17:26.720
so this is after you've lost the money from?

17:26.720 --> 17:27.040
Yeah.

17:27.040 --> 17:29.360
So this sort of just lending the dollar stopped working

17:29.360 --> 17:29.680
basically.

17:29.680 --> 17:31.040
And I had to realize, I had to think like,

17:31.040 --> 17:31.520
we're going to have to,

17:32.560 --> 17:33.840
we're going to have to figure out a smarter way

17:33.840 --> 17:34.640
to make money.

17:34.640 --> 17:37.600
And so the history of this is actually quite interesting,

17:37.600 --> 17:37.760
right?

17:37.760 --> 17:39.120
So I was an interest rates trader.

17:39.120 --> 17:40.240
We're going to get a bit technical here,

17:40.240 --> 17:41.280
but we'll keep it simple.

17:43.280 --> 17:47.120
So in 2008, all the interest rates in the,

17:47.120 --> 17:48.960
in the rich world collapsed to zero,

17:48.960 --> 17:51.040
because central bank cuts rates.

17:51.040 --> 17:52.080
We want to boost the economy.

17:52.080 --> 17:53.040
The economy is really shit.

17:53.040 --> 17:54.160
So everybody cut their rates.

17:54.160 --> 17:56.640
And then our job became basically

17:56.640 --> 17:58.080
to bet on when more rates go up again.

17:59.200 --> 18:01.360
And rates will go up when the economy recovers.

18:01.360 --> 18:02.640
You know, that's a simplification,

18:02.640 --> 18:04.960
but you know, that's basically what happens.

18:05.680 --> 18:08.400
And interest rates stayed zero from 2008

18:08.400 --> 18:11.200
until this year basically, 2022,

18:11.200 --> 18:12.160
which is 14 years.

18:12.720 --> 18:14.640
And in every single one of those years,

18:15.840 --> 18:17.280
markets and economies predicted

18:17.280 --> 18:18.640
that rates would go up the next year,

18:19.200 --> 18:21.600
which was wrong 12, 13 years in a row,

18:21.600 --> 18:22.880
which is interesting, right?

18:23.440 --> 18:25.120
These are the best paid guys in the world

18:25.840 --> 18:26.560
to do this thing.

18:27.200 --> 18:28.400
And they're wrong year after year.

18:28.400 --> 18:30.880
This is like if you studied, you know,

18:30.880 --> 18:32.160
weather forecasting at uni

18:32.160 --> 18:34.240
and you went to work at like the Met

18:34.240 --> 18:36.080
and you saw that every single year,

18:36.080 --> 18:37.280
every single day that like tomorrow's

18:37.280 --> 18:39.360
going to be like sunny and 30 degrees,

18:39.360 --> 18:40.640
you know, and they're always wrong.

18:41.280 --> 18:45.520
So, you know, this happened in 2008.

18:45.520 --> 18:46.880
And they're like, it'll get better next year.

18:46.880 --> 18:48.320
It didn't 2009.

18:48.320 --> 18:49.680
Okay, it was quite serious.

18:49.680 --> 18:51.280
Maybe next year, 2010.

18:51.280 --> 18:52.960
They're like, okay, well, just give it one more year.

18:52.960 --> 18:55.520
And sort of, by sort of late 2010,

18:55.520 --> 18:57.520
I'd seen these guys be wrong for two and a half years.

18:57.520 --> 19:01.920
And I started to think like, maybe they're just wrong.

19:01.920 --> 19:03.280
Maybe there isn't a recovery.

19:03.280 --> 19:05.520
I think the big thing for me was,

19:05.520 --> 19:07.280
because I came from a poor background,

19:08.080 --> 19:11.120
and, you know, I still had the same friends,

19:11.120 --> 19:11.840
the same family.

19:11.840 --> 19:16.560
I could see that things were getting actively worse

19:16.560 --> 19:17.520
for people from where I'm from.

19:17.520 --> 19:19.600
And it was like, well, how do you expect,

19:19.600 --> 19:21.920
the idea behind cutting interest rates

19:21.920 --> 19:23.200
is you get people spending money on

19:23.200 --> 19:24.400
because you can borrow money cheaply.

19:24.400 --> 19:25.600
Oh, it's great, spend money.

19:25.600 --> 19:28.480
But I look at the situation of my friends and family

19:28.480 --> 19:29.200
that I grew up with.

19:30.880 --> 19:32.880
These guys are losing their homes, right?

19:32.880 --> 19:33.920
Their parents had property.

19:33.920 --> 19:35.040
They'll never own property.

19:35.040 --> 19:36.880
So they're getting poor year after year.

19:37.440 --> 19:39.120
How the fuck are they going to start spending money

19:39.120 --> 19:40.960
because you give them access to a cheap loan?

19:40.960 --> 19:42.480
They don't even get access to that money.

19:42.480 --> 19:44.400
They can't go and borrow money at zero percent.

19:44.400 --> 19:44.880
You know what I mean?

19:44.880 --> 19:47.920
So I started to look at this and I started to think,

19:48.880 --> 19:50.720
I don't see it happening.

19:50.720 --> 19:51.600
I don't see it happening.

19:51.600 --> 19:54.000
And I guess I was in this sort of quite unique position

19:54.000 --> 19:55.520
because there's not many people that go from

19:55.520 --> 19:58.480
poor backgrounds to working in trading nowadays.

19:58.480 --> 20:02.640
So I could see what it was like for ordinary people.

20:02.640 --> 20:04.000
And I could also see what it was like

20:04.000 --> 20:05.680
for these rich guys working in the city.

20:05.680 --> 20:06.960
You know, it's a bunch of millionaires working in the city.

20:06.960 --> 20:09.200
Do you also think because you started in 2008,

20:09.200 --> 20:10.960
you had no sort of prior expectations?

20:10.960 --> 20:13.120
Whereas somebody has been in the industry 25 years,

20:13.120 --> 20:14.960
they've seen lots of ups and downs.

20:14.960 --> 20:17.280
And so there's going to be a bunch of cognitive biases

20:17.280 --> 20:19.520
where they say, I was here in the mid-80s.

20:19.520 --> 20:20.720
I was here in the early 90s.

20:20.720 --> 20:22.160
I was here for .com.

20:22.160 --> 20:23.520
This is just the same.

20:23.520 --> 20:26.800
But actually you didn't have any of that because there's all you knew.

20:26.800 --> 20:28.320
I guess they're used to interest rates up and down.

20:28.320 --> 20:30.240
They weren't used to this sort of flat lining, I think.

20:30.880 --> 20:33.680
But you know, I think if you consider how long that went on for,

20:33.680 --> 20:36.320
you know, even at the beginning of 2020,

20:36.320 --> 20:38.480
people were still predicting rates going to go up later that year.

20:39.040 --> 20:40.480
That's 12 years.

20:40.480 --> 20:42.240
12 years of incorrect predictions.

20:42.240 --> 20:42.800
It's incredible.

20:42.800 --> 20:44.400
I think that's, you know,

20:44.400 --> 20:46.800
we could have a whole discussion about why it is that happens.

20:47.280 --> 20:50.800
And you know, I went back to Oxford 2017-2019

20:50.800 --> 20:51.840
and I asked one of the professors,

20:51.840 --> 20:53.200
we had an electoral interest rates.

20:54.720 --> 20:56.000
And I went up to him afterwards and I said,

20:56.000 --> 20:56.800
why do you think we were so,

20:56.800 --> 20:58.480
we were wrong on these interest rates for so long?

20:59.040 --> 21:01.120
And he said, oh no, we always knew rates would stay zero.

21:02.480 --> 21:04.480
And I was like, I didn't know what to say to that

21:04.480 --> 21:06.000
because, you know, this is my job, you know.

21:06.000 --> 21:08.480
I know for fact that these guys predicted interest rates

21:08.480 --> 21:09.680
would go back up every single year.

21:09.680 --> 21:11.280
And I was like, no, you didn't.

21:11.280 --> 21:12.000
It was like, yeah, we knew.

21:12.000 --> 21:12.800
We knew.

21:12.800 --> 21:14.240
I just said, I'm going to go home.

21:14.240 --> 21:16.480
I'm going to send you the data and then we're going to talk about it.

21:16.480 --> 21:17.680
2017, he said that.

21:17.680 --> 21:18.320
Yeah, 2017.

21:18.320 --> 21:20.000
Because even you had Janet Yellen before then

21:20.000 --> 21:22.480
putting up US interest rates in like 2014, 2015,

21:22.480 --> 21:24.240
they were saying, oh, we're going to try and go back to normal.

21:24.240 --> 21:26.800
Yeah, which eventually came down again.

21:26.800 --> 21:27.280
Yeah.

21:27.280 --> 21:30.240
And I said, so I sent him the data and he was like, oh, that's interesting.

21:30.240 --> 21:31.840
Yeah, we have been wrong for 10 years.

21:31.840 --> 21:33.360
And his guy, right,

21:35.120 --> 21:37.840
professor of macroeconomics at Oxford University,

21:38.400 --> 21:39.920
he's been wrong for 10 years.

21:39.920 --> 21:42.400
Not only has he been wrong for 10 years in a row,

21:42.400 --> 21:44.320
he's not realized that he's done that.

21:45.040 --> 21:47.040
That is the level we are at here of economics.

21:48.080 --> 21:50.240
But look at this guy, rich guy, rich family.

21:50.240 --> 21:51.760
He used to wear a nice snake skin belt.

21:51.760 --> 21:52.320
You know what I mean?

21:54.080 --> 21:55.360
He doesn't get hurt, does he?

21:55.360 --> 21:57.360
This guy's wrong 10 years in a row.

21:57.360 --> 21:58.640
He never gets hurt.

21:58.640 --> 21:59.920
Of course, he doesn't notice.

21:59.920 --> 22:00.400
You know what I mean?

22:00.400 --> 22:01.200
I always, you know,

22:01.200 --> 22:03.200
I wrote some articles at the beginning of COVID saying like,

22:03.200 --> 22:05.360
this is going to cause a massive increase in inequality.

22:05.360 --> 22:07.120
It's going to cause a massive increase in house prices.

22:07.120 --> 22:08.800
It's going to cause a massive inflationary crisis.

22:08.800 --> 22:09.200
Okay.

22:09.200 --> 22:11.120
At the same time, Larry Elliott,

22:11.120 --> 22:13.760
like chief economics editor at The Guardian,

22:13.760 --> 22:15.360
was writing house prices are going to collapse.

22:15.360 --> 22:15.600
Okay.

22:16.400 --> 22:17.520
That was obviously wrong.

22:17.520 --> 22:18.880
Who's punishing Larry Elliott?

22:18.880 --> 22:19.680
You know what I mean?

22:19.680 --> 22:21.920
But why was, wait, so at the beginning of COVID?

22:21.920 --> 22:23.920
Yeah, because there was briefly,

22:23.920 --> 22:25.440
there was briefly a buyer's market

22:26.000 --> 22:29.600
because you did have lots of people with like student homes,

22:29.600 --> 22:31.600
buy to let landlords, they just thought,

22:31.600 --> 22:34.240
you know what, this is going to be unoccupied for God knows how long.

22:34.240 --> 22:35.760
The margins are low, you should get rid.

22:35.760 --> 22:38.160
So you got, you did get a big flood of those properties.

22:38.160 --> 22:39.120
For a brief moment, yeah.

22:39.120 --> 22:40.080
For about three, four months.

22:40.080 --> 22:42.640
I remember, and it was less that the market fell,

22:42.640 --> 22:43.760
there was just uncertainty.

22:43.760 --> 22:45.280
So you could get real value.

22:45.280 --> 22:45.600
Yeah.

22:45.600 --> 22:47.360
But I think what people were missing was,

22:47.360 --> 22:49.360
we knew at the beginning of COVID,

22:49.360 --> 22:51.360
the government is going to give a shit ton of money out.

