we could enter a bit of a spiral here

57:59.360 --> 58:01.680
where inflation stays high and interest rates stay high.

58:02.480 --> 58:04.640
But then what happened is the market rejected that.

58:04.640 --> 58:08.960
So I think it depends on what the government does.

58:09.760 --> 58:11.760
And unfortunately, both outcomes are bad, right?

58:11.760 --> 58:14.480
If the government decides to just churn money out,

58:14.480 --> 58:16.480
which ends up going, ending up with the rich,

58:16.480 --> 58:19.920
then you will see a big rise in interest rates

58:19.920 --> 58:21.200
and a big rise in inflation.

58:21.200 --> 58:24.480
And that causes this kind of conflict, right?

58:24.480 --> 58:26.480
Because in the long run, assets have to go up,

58:26.480 --> 58:28.240
but people can't get mortgages.

58:28.240 --> 58:30.320
And I think what that would lead to in the end is basically,

58:30.320 --> 58:31.280
people who have used mortgages

58:31.280 --> 58:33.680
will have to sell their houses to the people who have the cash.

58:33.680 --> 58:36.320
Because I mean, you and I sit here and you think,

58:36.320 --> 58:39.200
oh, interest rates go up, that makes it harder to buy a house.

58:39.200 --> 58:41.440
A ton of people don't need a mortgage to buy a house nowadays,

58:41.440 --> 58:44.080
because the really rich are stacking up so much cash.

58:44.080 --> 58:45.920
And they are the guys who get paid

58:45.920 --> 58:47.760
the high rates of interest on this cash.

58:49.520 --> 58:53.040
But now it looks more likely, and this is very up in the air,

58:53.040 --> 58:54.320
we don't know what the government's going to do,

58:54.320 --> 58:57.680
that they're going to move towards a kind of austerity light model.

58:57.760 --> 58:59.440
And I think that will probably take us,

58:59.440 --> 59:02.400
if they do that to a more post-2008 situation,

59:02.400 --> 59:04.560
where it's immiseration for ordinary people.

59:05.680 --> 59:06.880
Inflation will eventually come down,

59:06.880 --> 59:09.920
because the middle class has their spending power so badly hit.

59:10.880 --> 59:13.520
And house prices end up going up,

59:13.520 --> 59:14.880
because the rich have so much money,

59:14.880 --> 59:17.040
and they need, they want assets,

59:17.040 --> 59:18.800
they want to buy things with that money.

59:20.240 --> 59:22.400
And I think that's the bigger risk,

59:22.400 --> 59:26.080
because I think people don't realize how much it,

59:26.160 --> 59:28.560
a lot of people in the middle of society economically,

59:28.560 --> 59:30.880
don't realize how much it hurts their family,

59:30.880 --> 59:31.920
especially the kids and their grandkids,

59:31.920 --> 59:32.880
when house prices go up.

59:34.800 --> 59:35.920
I think that is the risk,

59:35.920 --> 59:38.160
but medium to long term,

59:38.160 --> 59:40.160
I'm very confident that house prices will go up.

59:40.160 --> 59:45.920
And that's a very, that's a very anti-consensus view at the moment.

59:45.920 --> 59:48.720
But the fact is, and this is the thing people keep missing,

59:48.720 --> 59:50.400
and have missed this at the beginning of COVID,

59:50.400 --> 59:53.680
the rich are stacking up so much cash here,

59:53.680 --> 59:55.040
and they're not going to sit on it.

59:55.040 --> 59:56.000
They're going to use it to buy assets.

59:56.000 --> 59:58.000
And I think one thing that will have to happen,

59:58.000 --> 01:00:00.240
is the government will end up being forced

01:00:00.240 --> 01:00:03.920
to relax mortgage requirements, because...

01:00:03.920 --> 01:00:04.800
We're all doing this, right?

01:00:04.800 --> 01:00:06.480
That's why 50 year mortgage products and whatnot.

01:00:06.480 --> 01:00:09.520
They need to keep people being homeowners,

01:00:09.520 --> 01:00:11.440
but they also want to make the rich richer.

01:00:11.440 --> 01:00:13.280
Well, how do you do that, bigger mortgages?

01:00:13.280 --> 01:00:15.200
Then you can own your home technically,

01:00:15.200 --> 01:00:17.440
you own your 800, 900 grand home,

01:00:17.440 --> 01:00:19.520
but you also owe 800 grand debt to the rich.

01:00:19.520 --> 01:00:21.840
So you've got the home, but they've got the actual wealth.

01:00:22.640 --> 01:00:23.920
So I think that will happen.

01:00:23.920 --> 01:00:25.920
And I think the way that we fight that,

01:00:25.920 --> 01:00:29.360
is we have to make this connection between the distribution

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:31.120
and the quality of life of ordinary people.

01:00:31.120 --> 01:00:32.320
We have to make that connection,

01:00:32.320 --> 01:00:34.560
because if we don't make that, people's lives get worse,

01:00:34.560 --> 01:00:35.760
and they don't understand why.

01:00:35.760 --> 01:00:36.720
They're like, well, I've got more money,

01:00:36.720 --> 01:00:38.320
my house price is going up, I should be richer.

01:00:38.960 --> 01:00:41.200
But if you are getting relatively poor art,

01:00:41.200 --> 01:00:42.640
then you will get less stuff.

01:00:42.640 --> 01:00:44.400
We've had in the last three years,

01:00:44.400 --> 01:00:46.080
the biggest and fastest ever increase

01:00:46.080 --> 01:00:47.600
in inequality in the country.

01:00:47.600 --> 01:00:49.280
And the biggest and fastest decrease

01:00:49.280 --> 01:00:51.280
in living standards in peacetime,

01:00:51.280 --> 01:00:52.640
and no one's connecting the two.

01:00:52.640 --> 01:00:55.120
And I think it's such an opportunity that we're missing.

01:00:55.120 --> 01:00:56.880
We need to say, look, you are getting poorer

01:00:56.880 --> 01:00:58.320
because of that increase in inequalities.

01:00:59.120 --> 01:01:00.800
It's not a complicated connection.

01:01:00.800 --> 01:01:02.960
You increase inequality, you improve their living standards,

01:01:02.960 --> 01:01:03.760
you decrease yours.

01:01:03.760 --> 01:01:04.800
I'm kind of surprised, actually,

01:01:04.800 --> 01:01:06.640
the middle class aren't more angry about it.

01:01:06.640 --> 01:01:09.120
Like, the people that shop at Waitrose,

01:01:09.120 --> 01:01:11.840
very affluent, looking to retire in a couple of years,

01:01:12.960 --> 01:01:15.280
there's many, many people like that who are very, very,

01:01:15.280 --> 01:01:18.240
I'm not saying they all vote Labour or Tory or Lib Dem,

01:01:18.240 --> 01:01:20.000
they do all three, or they don't vote at all.

01:01:20.560 --> 01:01:22.160
But they know that they're really

01:01:23.520 --> 01:01:24.880
fucking their kids and their grandkids.

01:01:24.880 --> 01:01:25.920
They know that.

01:01:25.920 --> 01:01:27.280
That's the connection we need to make.

01:01:27.280 --> 01:01:28.400
But they know that.

01:01:29.520 --> 01:01:30.880
Because there's polling out there, for instance,

01:01:30.880 --> 01:01:32.720
about should house prices fall?

01:01:32.720 --> 01:01:34.000
Which is really interesting.

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:35.520
And actually, over 50% of the public

01:01:35.520 --> 01:01:37.440
say it would be in the public interest

01:01:37.440 --> 01:01:38.800
for house prices to fall.

01:01:38.800 --> 01:01:40.400
That doesn't mean they want house prices to fall

01:01:40.400 --> 01:01:42.080
because it's not necessarily in their rational self-interest,

01:01:42.080 --> 01:01:43.600
but they know what needs to happen.

01:01:44.560 --> 01:01:46.960
There's a lot of guilt out there, surely, amongst those people.

01:01:46.960 --> 01:01:48.000
You know there's this article,

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:49.360
which always appears in the newspapers,

01:01:49.360 --> 01:01:52.880
which is how I bought a house by saving up

01:01:52.880 --> 01:01:54.160
and stop buying coffees.

01:01:54.160 --> 01:01:56.400
And famously, it always has, like, in there,

01:01:56.400 --> 01:01:58.720
and then I got 300 grand from my mum, like, hidden in there.

01:02:00.400 --> 01:02:02.080
Those articles, in my opinion,

01:02:03.120 --> 01:02:05.920
are to assuage the concerns of older property owners.

01:02:06.480 --> 01:02:07.920
Because older property owners,

01:02:07.920 --> 01:02:10.720
which is massively the voting base of the Conservative Party,

01:02:11.920 --> 01:02:13.760
have been to a large degree protected.

01:02:13.760 --> 01:02:14.640
You know, so, you know,

01:02:14.640 --> 01:02:15.680
my parents have always been poor,

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:16.880
but they own their own property.

01:02:16.880 --> 01:02:18.240
And that means that, very likely,

01:02:18.240 --> 01:02:20.320
they'll be able to live to some degree comfortably

01:02:20.320 --> 01:02:20.960
until their retirement.

01:02:20.960 --> 01:02:22.640
They'll probably have to dissafe that property, right,

01:02:22.640 --> 01:02:23.600
and they'll lose the home.

01:02:24.160 --> 01:02:24.960
But they've been protected,

01:02:24.960 --> 01:02:26.480
even though they've been poor their whole lives, right?

01:02:27.040 --> 01:02:29.120
But if they were to look more broadly

01:02:29.120 --> 01:02:30.480
and to look at their kids and say,

01:02:30.480 --> 01:02:32.640
oh, well, you know, how are my kids going to be?

01:02:32.640 --> 01:02:34.320
They'd be like, they'd have to look realistically

01:02:34.320 --> 01:02:35.920
and be like, fuck, that's what they earn.

01:02:35.920 --> 01:02:36.960
That's the house prices.

01:02:38.880 --> 01:02:39.840
What's their pension?

01:02:39.840 --> 01:02:40.960
What's their retirement look like?

01:02:41.840 --> 01:02:42.640
How do I have elderly care?

01:02:42.640 --> 01:02:43.840
But people don't want to think about that.

01:02:43.840 --> 01:02:45.840
And then if the media tells you, well, listen, don't worry.

01:02:46.800 --> 01:02:48.000
You know what kids are like?

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:48.880
They're a bit silly.

01:02:48.880 --> 01:02:49.760
They waste their money.

01:02:50.560 --> 01:02:51.200
They'll sort out.

01:02:51.200 --> 01:02:52.480
They'll stop buying the coffees.

01:02:52.480 --> 01:02:53.360
They'll stop buying that stuff.

01:02:53.360 --> 01:02:54.320
And they'll be okay.

01:02:54.960 --> 01:02:56.960
Those articles are there to tell.

01:02:56.960 --> 01:02:59.680
And, you know, it's easy to convince someone

01:02:59.680 --> 01:03:01.200
something they want to believe, right?

01:03:01.200 --> 01:03:03.440
Those guys grow out there and sell to older people

01:03:03.440 --> 01:03:04.880
that you're protected.

01:03:04.880 --> 01:03:06.320
And we know you might look bad for your kids,

01:03:06.320 --> 01:03:06.960
but don't worry.

01:03:07.760 --> 01:03:08.480
We've got that.

01:03:08.480 --> 01:03:09.600
They don't have that.

01:03:09.600 --> 01:03:10.880
And we need to counter that.

01:03:10.880 --> 01:03:13.120
And it's not easy because our message is,

01:03:13.120 --> 01:03:14.080
in some ways, unpalatable,

01:03:14.080 --> 01:03:15.360
which is if we stay on this path,

01:03:15.920 --> 01:03:16.800
your kids and your grandkids

01:03:16.800 --> 01:03:18.480
will have very, very difficult economic lives.

01:03:19.520 --> 01:03:20.880
But we need to make that case.

01:03:20.880 --> 01:03:23.120
And, you know, those are the people,

01:03:23.120 --> 01:03:24.240
in a sense, that we need to win.

01:03:24.240 --> 01:03:26.400
And, you know, it's their kids and their grandkids being hurt.

01:03:27.040 --> 01:03:29.840
And we need to find a way to communicate to them clearly

01:03:29.840 --> 01:03:31.680
and compassionately so they don't feel attacked.

01:03:31.680 --> 01:03:34.000
Look, we are trying to protect your kids and your grandkids.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:35.280
We're not attacking you.

01:03:35.280 --> 01:03:36.800
You know, where are your kids going to live?

01:03:37.360 --> 01:03:38.480
What is their life going to be like?

01:03:38.480 --> 01:03:40.400
Are your kids going to be able to afford to have kids of their own?

01:03:40.400 --> 01:03:43.040
You know, that is the message that I think we need to be making.

01:03:44.320 --> 01:03:46.080
If there's a young person watching this

01:03:46.080 --> 01:03:48.240
and they're thinking, I really want to get on the housing ladder,

01:03:49.520 --> 01:03:52.240
and then there's loads of calculations at play, right?

01:03:52.240 --> 01:03:53.600
Do I need to maybe move?

01:03:54.560 --> 01:03:56.800
Or should I prioritize, et cetera, et cetera?

01:03:56.800 --> 01:03:57.840
Presumably, you would still,

01:03:57.840 --> 01:03:58.880
it's not often on Navarro media,

01:03:58.880 --> 01:04:00.480
we talk about financial advice.

01:04:00.480 --> 01:04:02.320
But presumably, you would therefore say to them,

01:04:02.320 --> 01:04:03.840
given what you said five minutes ago about,

01:04:03.840 --> 01:04:05.920
you think house prices will continue to go up,

01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:07.040
that they should do that.

01:04:07.040 --> 01:04:09.600
I've been saying this, you know, consistently.

01:04:09.600 --> 01:04:10.480
If you can buy property.

01:04:10.480 --> 01:04:11.920
Don't wait for the market to go down.

01:04:11.920 --> 01:04:13.280
If you can do it, get on the ladder.

01:04:13.280 --> 01:04:14.640
If you can, if you can.

01:04:14.720 --> 01:04:16.880
Listen, if you don't have property,

01:04:16.880 --> 01:04:17.760
that's not a flat position,

01:04:17.760 --> 01:04:18.800
you're short one property,

01:04:18.800 --> 01:04:20.320
because you've got to live somewhere.

01:04:20.320 --> 01:04:22.160
You know, the first thing you should be looking to do,

01:04:22.160 --> 01:04:25.840
and I totally understand that in today's economy,

01:04:25.840 --> 01:04:28.080
that means taking 300, 400,

01:04:28.080 --> 01:04:30.640
if you're in London, 600, 700 grand of debt maybe.

01:04:30.640 --> 01:04:32.960
And that is risky, and that is unappealing.

01:04:32.960 --> 01:04:35.040
And I wish that we were not in that situation.

01:04:35.040 --> 01:04:37.440
But the truth is, if you don't own a property,

01:04:37.440 --> 01:04:40.560
you are in a very precarious financial position.

01:04:40.560 --> 01:04:43.040
And the best way you can get yourself out of that,

01:04:43.040 --> 01:04:44.160
is to get yourself a property.

01:04:44.160 --> 01:04:46.720
And you know, I wish that didn't mean

01:04:46.720 --> 01:04:48.160
taking a massive, massive mortgage.

01:04:48.160 --> 01:04:49.920
And I can't pretend to people

01:04:49.920 --> 01:04:51.520
that you're not taking a massive financial risk

01:04:51.520 --> 01:04:52.080
of buying a property.

01:04:52.080 --> 01:04:54.720
But the truth is, you are also taking a massive financial risk

01:04:54.720 --> 01:04:55.840
of not buying a property.

01:04:55.840 --> 01:04:57.440
Because look what's happening to rents.

01:04:57.440 --> 01:04:58.640
Look what's happening to their house prices.

01:04:58.640 --> 01:05:00.480
You know, there's people in London now,

01:05:00.480 --> 01:05:02.000
they don't even know where they're going to live.

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:03.440
You know, and you know,

01:05:03.440 --> 01:05:05.360
if you don't have a property, you are short one property.

01:05:05.360 --> 01:05:07.680
You need to get that, just to make yourself secure.

01:05:07.680 --> 01:05:11.760
And I have to say when I say that, that I know,

01:05:11.840 --> 01:05:13.520
I know full world, that that is advice,

01:05:13.520 --> 01:05:14.800
that is impossible for a lot of people.

01:05:14.800 --> 01:05:15.600
And I understand that.

01:05:15.600 --> 01:05:15.920
Of course.

01:05:17.680 --> 01:05:19.440
But that is, you know, I have to tell people that,

01:05:19.440 --> 01:05:19.920
and it's true.

01:05:20.560 --> 01:05:22.480
And if you are in a situation where you can't,

01:05:23.040 --> 01:05:26.720
then you know, support me, follow my channel,

01:05:26.720 --> 01:05:28.560
people like you, so we can come out and explain,

01:05:28.560 --> 01:05:31.600
look, that it could be possible if we change things.

01:05:31.600 --> 01:05:33.520
I mean, I'll provide an example here.

01:05:33.520 --> 01:05:37.920
So I left, I left London because I'm with my now wife,

01:05:37.920 --> 01:05:39.040
because we wanted to have children.

01:05:39.040 --> 01:05:41.200
And we knew that we had to own somewhere

01:05:41.280 --> 01:05:43.360
to do that, because we, we couldn't,

01:05:43.360 --> 01:05:46.480
we'd love to rent if you had five year, 10 years,

01:05:46.480 --> 01:05:48.320
you didn't have a massive increase, et cetera,

01:05:48.320 --> 01:05:49.920
and kind of sort of security around housing

01:05:49.920 --> 01:05:51.360
that you say maybe have in Germany.

01:05:51.360 --> 01:05:52.400
We don't have that here.

01:05:52.400 --> 01:05:53.920
So we knew that we had to buy somewhere.

01:05:53.920 --> 01:05:55.520
That meant we had to move out of London.

01:05:56.240 --> 01:05:58.880
We did buy somewhere on the south coast.

01:05:59.760 --> 01:06:06.160
And doing that, just open my eyes so much as to,

01:06:06.160 --> 01:06:08.640
it's even worse than you think, if you're renting,

01:06:08.640 --> 01:06:09.840
how rigged the system is.

01:06:10.400 --> 01:06:12.640
The minute we accessed the mortgage,

01:06:12.640 --> 01:06:15.040
we didn't pay any stamp duty, that went.

01:06:16.160 --> 01:06:19.840
We then, that house in two years has gained more in value

01:06:19.840 --> 01:06:20.720
than I've earned working.

01:06:21.440 --> 01:06:23.600
We actually bought in a really good moment

01:06:23.600 --> 01:06:24.880
right at the beginning of the COVID crisis,

01:06:24.880 --> 01:06:27.680
where lots of, like I say, sort of student property developers

01:06:27.680 --> 01:06:29.040
just wanted to get rid of their assets, right?

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:32.400
And I just feel like, and then as we're remortgaging,

01:06:32.400 --> 01:06:34.800
fortunately we remortgaged just before all this happened,

01:06:34.800 --> 01:06:36.320
you've got people saying, yeah, you can,

01:06:36.320 --> 01:06:37.680
you can borrow against the increase

01:06:37.680 --> 01:06:38.800
in the value of the house.

01:06:38.880 --> 01:06:41.440
And you think, this is nuts.

01:06:41.440 --> 01:06:43.520
And yet there are tens of millions of people in this country

01:06:43.520 --> 01:06:47.840
who think it's not normal, not acceptable, they're virtuous.

01:06:47.840 --> 01:06:51.280
And it's like, you keep on being rewarded for being lucky

01:06:51.280 --> 01:06:53.440
and then you get rewarded again and rewarded again.

01:06:53.440 --> 01:06:54.800
The people who actually down on their luck

01:06:54.800 --> 01:06:57.440
because they couldn't get the initial cash capital for the deposit,

01:06:57.440 --> 01:06:58.640
they keep on being punished.

01:06:59.280 --> 01:07:02.480
And I just feel like, how do we get that?

01:07:02.480 --> 01:07:04.880
I know renters know they're in a bad situation,

01:07:04.880 --> 01:07:07.200
but it's like, it's so much worse than you even realize.

01:07:08.160 --> 01:07:12.160
Yeah, I mean, it's, you know, my channel,

01:07:12.160 --> 01:07:14.160
it's mainly about sort of economics and politics,

01:07:14.160 --> 01:07:16.640
but we do do sort of, we talk about investing,

01:07:16.640 --> 01:07:17.760
we talk about buying property.

01:07:17.760 --> 01:07:20.560
And it's hard because I get so many messages like,

01:07:21.440 --> 01:07:22.720
you know, what can I do to make money?

01:07:22.720 --> 01:07:25.360
And the truth is like, you know, in the last years,

01:07:25.360 --> 01:07:27.600
we've seen this big increase in sort of crypto

01:07:27.600 --> 01:07:28.640
and online trading.

01:07:28.640 --> 01:07:32.000
And it sells this dream that you can sort of invest your way to wealth.

01:07:32.560 --> 01:07:35.520
But the truth is, you know, like, I live off of my assets,

01:07:35.520 --> 01:07:37.440
you know, I'm a wealthy individual, I live off of my assets,

01:07:37.440 --> 01:07:40.160
you know, if you come, if you come to me with like 500 grand,

01:07:40.720 --> 01:07:43.760
then if you make 5% a year, you can make 25 grand,

01:07:43.760 --> 01:07:44.800
you can live off that.

01:07:44.800 --> 01:07:48.560
If you come to me with 10, 15 grand, you make 5% a year,

01:07:48.560 --> 01:07:50.640
you know, you're never going to make 100 pound.

01:07:50.640 --> 01:07:54.560
You know, so it's sort of, this is, and the thing is,

01:07:55.200 --> 01:07:57.520
I want to tell people this, buy a property if you can,

01:07:57.520 --> 01:07:58.640
because it's good financial advice,

01:07:58.640 --> 01:08:00.320
but I just know it's impossible.

01:08:00.320 --> 01:08:02.640
And then that's why I think what is really interesting,

01:08:02.640 --> 01:08:04.880
you look at the journey that Martin Lewis has been on,

01:08:04.960 --> 01:08:06.800
my Lewis Money-Saving Expert, I guess people know,

01:08:07.920 --> 01:08:10.160
he's this guy that's like, protect your interests,

01:08:10.160 --> 01:08:12.080
do what's good for you, change your mortgage provider,

01:08:12.080 --> 01:08:13.360
change your electricity provider.

01:08:13.360 --> 01:08:16.240
